etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in The Wycliffite Bible (early version). From dung + -y

definitions: Of land, earth, etc.: rich in dung or other fertilizing matter; well dunged; fertile, productive.
Containing or characterized by the presence of dung; specifically covered in or spattered with dung; soiled or polluted with dung or filth; dirty, filthy; mucky, muddy.
Despicable, contemptible, foul; base, worthless; vile, degrading. rare after 17th century.
Designating a god or idol regarded as false, detestable, or abominable. Chiefly in biblical contexts. Compare "dunghill".
Characteristic of or suggestive of dung; of, relating to, or arising from dung.
